==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Daggle
<hw>Dag"gle</hw> <pr>(d⟦acr⟧g"g'l)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Daggled</conjf>
<pr>(-g'ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Daggling</conjf>
<pr>(-gl⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Freq. of <ets>dag</ets>, v. t.,
1.]</ety> <def>To trail, so as to wet or befoul; to make wet and limp;
to moisten.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The warrior's very plume, I say,⟦br⟧
Was <qex>daggled</qex> by the dashing spray.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Daggle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Daggle
<hw>Dag"gle</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To run, go, or trail one's self
through water, mud, or slush; to draggle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor, like a puppy [have I] <qex>daggled</qex> through the
town.</q> <rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj></p>

<p><ent>Daggle-tailed</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Daggle-tail</ent>⟦br⟧
